3. Submit the List of PPA (complete with necessary details) for audit at the beginning of every year;
4. Post the information in the List of PPA in appropriate places using the prescribed sizes of signboards / public notices;
5. Inform the concerned audit team (within 10-day after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity) that the signboards / public notices are already posted (for validation purposes); and
6. Maintain records on the Project Status of PPA (updated on the basis of the prescribed monthly Monitoring Report of PPA verified by the COA TAS).

We recommended that Management enforce provisions under COA Circular 2013-04 including existing rules and regulations concerning inspection and acceptance of procurements by:

notifying the concerned auditor prior to the inspection and acceptance of procurements including any stage of completion of any particular project;
preparing monthly monitoring report of PPAs verified by the COA-TAS;
maintaining an updated “Project Status” based on the data of the monthly monitoring report of PPAs;
providing the concerned SA and ATL, at the beginning of each year, with a list of all PPAs including pertinent information thereof as enumerated under COA Circular 2013-004; and
informing the SA and ATL, within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity, that the appropriate signboards are already posted for the SA and ATL to validate the same.

We recommended that the LGU should strictly enforce the provisions of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual for LGUs and the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standard (PPSAS), in particular to Sections 114 and 124 of the Manual and PPSAS 17 which mandates the following: 


the chief accountant should maintain PPE Ledger Card for each category of PPE.  Such ledger cards should contain the details of the PPE account in the inventory control account in the general ledger; 

the general services officer (GSO) or the municipal treasurer, as the case maybe, should maintain stock cards and property cards for

supplies and PPE to account for the receipt and disposition of the same and, that,, the balance per stock card / property cards should always reconcile with the ledger cards of the accounting unit and other property records like Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);  

the local chief executive should cause for the conduct of physical count of PPE annually and the preparation of the annual Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) which has to be submitted to the concerned Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and 

infrastructure assets should be recognized in the books of accounts as PPE so that assets recorded in the registry of public infrastructures should then be brought back to the books to start in the year 2016.
